/>

<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · The unit on your wall is not the unit at Lowes</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Permanent-mount patio heaters are a different category. Different parts. Different repair logic.</h2>

    <p>Permanent-mount patio heaters in Beverly Hills, Bel Air, Malibu, Calabasas, and Newport Beach are not the patio store propane heaters with the round mushroom top. These are $1,500 to $5,000 per unit, hardwired into natural gas plumbing or 240V electric, mounted to ceilings or walls, often arranged in groups of three to five across a patio. When one stops working, replacing it is not a $300 trip to Lowes. It's a $2,500 OEM order plus install plus matching the others to keep the array consistent.</p>

    <p>We repair these. Most issues are not catastrophic. The most common failure on a Bromic Tungsten Smart-Heat is a $36 thermocouple. The most common Infratech issue is a $90 to $385 element module depending on wattage. Fire Sense and AEI Sunpak: gas valves and ignition assemblies. The repairs that actually need full unit replacement are rare. Maybe one in fifteen calls. The other fourteen are component-level fixes that buy another five to ten years of service from a unit that already cost the homeowner thousands.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 FAILURE MODES BY BRAND -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Typical failure modes by brand</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What actually fails, by manufacturer.</h2>

    <div class="brand-block">
      <h3>Bromic Tungsten / Platinum (gas, permanent mount)</h3>
      <p>The thermocouple is failure number one. BH8280036 on the Tungsten Portable, similar part on permanent-mount Tungsten and Platinum lines. Salt air on coastal patios oxidizes it. Heater lights, won't stay lit, that's the thermocouple every time. $36 to $80 part, 30-minute swap. Failure number two: gas valve sticks after a long inactive summer. Failure number three: ignition module wiring corrosion at the wall mount junction.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="brand-block">
      <h3>Infratech (electric, hardwired 240V)</h3>
      <p>Element burns out, element module replacement. The W-Series elements run $200 to $450 depending on wattage. Switch failures on the hardwired in-wall control are common in 7+ year installs because resistive contacts pit from cycling. We carry W-1500SS, W-2500SS, and W-4000SS modules on the van. Diagnostic distinction that matters: element shorted to ground requires replacement; element faded or single-zone failure usually module-only.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="brand-block">
      <h3>Fire Sense (gas)</h3>
      <p>Mid-tier permanent units. Common: pilot assembly clogged from spider webs (the pilot orifice is a 0.011" hole, perfect spider home), thermocouple weak after three to four years, gas valve diaphragm leak. Repair-friendly platform. Parts via authorized distributor, two to three day order. Models we see most: 60460 freestanding and several wall-mount variants.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="brand-block">
      <h3>AEI Sunpak (gas)</h3>
      <p>Premium hardwired units, $2,500 to $4,500 each. Heat exchanger longevity is excellent (15+ years), but the ignition assembly fails. Sunpak ignition kit S34S or S34S-TSH runs $180 to $280 part, 90-minute install. We've replaced these on SD25 units 12+ years old that otherwise look new.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="brand-block">
      <h3>SunStar (gas, infrared)</h3>
      <p>Less common in residential SoCal but show up in commercial and high-end residential. Tube-style infrared. Ceramic burner replacement is the typical major repair, $400 to $700.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 DIAGNOSIS PROCESS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · How we diagnose a patio heater</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">We work in this order. Every call.</h2>

    <ol class="diag-list">
      <li><strong>Power and gas at source.</strong> Is the breaker tripped? Is the gas shutoff valve on? 5% of "broken heater" calls are this.</li>
      <li><strong>Thermocouple millivolt test.</strong> Probe at the gas valve thermocouple terminal. Should read 18 to 30 mV during pilot. Below 14 mV the valve won't hold open. This single test diagnoses 60% of "won't stay lit" calls.</li>
      <li><strong>Pilot orifice inspection.</strong> Visual plus clean if needed. 5-minute check.</li>
      <li><strong>Igniter test.</strong> For electronic ignition, continuity check on the spark electrode and ground. For piezo, sound test. It should snap audibly.</li>
      <li><strong>Gas pressure check.</strong> At the regulator outlet, should match manufacturer spec for the unit (typically 4 to 7" WC for natural gas residential).</li>
      <li><strong>Element or burner inspection.</strong> For gas, look for corrosion, cracking, blockage. For electric, continuity test across element terminals.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>We do this every call. We don't guess, we test. The reason it matters: half of "needs new heater" diagnoses from competitors are actually a $40 to $80 part that wasn't tested for.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL REPAIR STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Real repair stories</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Recent jobs from the territory.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Composite examples; model numbers, ages, and prices reflect typical scope.</p>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Malibu · 5x Bromic Tungsten Smart-Heat permanent natural gas, 2021 install</h3>
      <p>Owner called because one wouldn't light. Tech tested thermocouple, failed (salt air corrosion). Replaced BH8280036, working. Tested the other four, three were below 16 mV and would have failed within the season. Replaced all five preemptively. Total: $120 diagnostic + 4 × $80 parts + 2 hours labor = $640. Owner's previous tech had quoted "needs new heater, $4,200 each" before we showed up.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Beverly Hills · 3x Infratech W-2500SS hardwired electric, ceiling-mount, 2018 install</h3>
      <p>Middle unit dark, others working. Element module test: open circuit. Replaced the W-2500SS module ($385 part), tested. Working. Total: $620 all-in. We could have sold a full unit replacement at $2,800. Didn't.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Newport Beach · AEI Sunpak SD25, 2015 install</h3>
      <p>Won't ignite. Thermocouple OK, gas pressure OK. Ignition module had failed. Replaced the S34S kit, tested. Working. Total: $120 + $245 part + 90 min labor = $510.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Pacific Palisades · Fire Sense 60460 freestanding</h3>
      <p>Pilot won't light. Pilot orifice clogged with web. 10-minute clean, no parts. Charged the $120 diagnostic, didn't bill labor for the 10-minute fix. Customer called us back six months later for the gas grill.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 HONEST SCOPE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Honest scope</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we service, what we don't.</h2>

    <p><strong>We service:</strong> Bromic, Infratech, Fire Sense, AEI Sunpak, SunStar, Solaira, Calcana, Schwank residential.</p>

    <p><strong>We don't service:</strong></p>
    <ul class="scope-list">
      <li><strong>Portable propane mushroom heaters from Costco or Lowes.</strong> No parts inventory makes service uneconomical for the customer. Replacement is cheaper than a service call on these.</li>
      <li><strong>Commercial restaurant exterior heating systems on multi-zone controllers.</strong> Different trade (outdoor commercial HVAC).</li>
      <li><strong>Industrial process radiant heat.</strong> Different category, different licensing.</li>
      <li><strong>Wood-burning outdoor heaters and chimineas.</strong> SCAQMD Rule 445 restricts new wood-burning installations across most of LA, OC, Riverside, and San Bernardino. We don't service or install these. Gas conversion is what we do.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Knowing what we don't do is part of the job. Property managers and premium homeowners value contractors who refer to the right specialist instead of fumbling through unfamiliar equipment.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 PRICING -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">06 · Pricing</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What patio heater repair actually costs.</h2>

    <table class="price-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Repair</th><th>Typical cost</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Diagnostic visit</td><td>$120, waived with repair</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Thermocouple replacement (gas)</td><td>$200 to $280 all-in</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Pilot assembly clean / minor</td><td>$150 to $220</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Gas valve replacement</td><td>$400 to $650</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Ignition module (electronic)</td><td>$350 to $550</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Element module (Infratech-style)</td><td>$450 to $700</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Burner replacement (gas)</td><td>$500 to $900</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Full unit installation (replacement)</td><td>Quote-based</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Warranty</td><td>90 days parts + labor</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p class="price-note">If anyone quotes you $1,500+ for a "patio heater repair" on a unit under 7 years old, get a second opinion. The ceiling for legitimate component-level repair on these brands is around $900 for the most complex jobs. Above that, it's usually a replacement decision being framed as a repair.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 07 WHY US -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">07 · Why call us for patio heaters</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Six reasons.</h2>

    <ul class="why-list">
      <li><strong>Parts on the van.</strong> Bromic thermocouples (BH8280036 and equivalents), Infratech W-Series modules, Fire Sense ignition kits, common AEI Sunpak parts. Most repairs are one-visit.</li>
      <li><strong>Coastal salt-air expertise.</strong> Malibu and Newport Beach service calls are roughly 40% of our patio heater work. We know what fails near the water and stock parts accordingly.</li>
      <li><strong>Honest replace-vs-repair calls.</strong> Sometimes a 14-year-old unit isn't worth fixing. We tell you. We're not on commission.</li>
      <li><strong>Multi-unit servicing.</strong> Most premium installs have three to six heaters. We service all of them in one visit so the array stays consistent.</li>
      <li><strong>Same-day across LA, OC, Ventura.</strong> Next-day for Riverside and San Bernardino. Phones answered 24/7.</li>
      <li><strong>EPA 608 certified.</strong> Covers Bromic Eclipse heat-pump heaters and a few electric variants with refrigerant components. See our <a href="/credentials/epa-certified/">EPA certification page</a>. CSLB #1138898.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Looking for the parent service hub? See our <a href="/outdoor/">outdoor appliance repair overview</a>. Sibling services: <a href="/outdoor/grill-repair/">grill repair</a>, <a href="/outdoor/fireplace-repair/">fireplace repair</a>, <a href="/outdoor/kitchen-repair/">outdoor kitchen repair</a>. For LA County coverage detail see our <a href="/los-angeles-county/">LA County service page</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 08 FAQ -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">08 · FAQ</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Patio heater repair, common questions.</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      {faqs.map((f) => (
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>{f.q}</summary>
          <p>{f.a}</p>
        </details>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 09 BOTTOM CTA -->
<section class="bottom-cta">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Patio Heater Down? Call Today.</h2>
    <p>Same-day across LA, OC, Ventura. Phones answered 24/7.</p>
    <div class="cta-row">
      <a href={phoneHref} class="btn-primary">☎ Call {phone}</a>
      <a href="/contact/" class="btn-secondary">Book Online</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

</Layout>

